    faqs: [
      { q: 'How much pea gravel do I need?', a: 'Multiply length (ft) × width (ft) × depth (in), then divide by 324 to get cubic yards. A 10×10 ft area at 2 inches deep needs 0.62 cubic yards (about 0.8 tons). For a playground at the ASTM-required 6 inches, a 15×15 ft area needs 4.2 cubic yards.' },
      { q: 'How deep should pea gravel be for a playground?', a: 'ASTM F1292 requires a minimum 6 inches of pea gravel for playground equipment up to 5 ft tall. Equipment 5–7 ft tall requires 9 inches. Equipment over 7 ft tall requires 12 inches. The critical fall height of your specific equipment determines the required depth - 6 inches is the absolute floor, not the standard.' },
      { q: 'How many tons of pea gravel do I need?', a: 'Pea gravel weighs 1.3 tons per cubic yard. Calculate cubic yards first (length × width × depth in inches ÷ 324), then multiply by 1.3. A 15×15 ft playground at 6 inches deep needs 4.2 yd³ × 1.3 = 5.4 tons.' },
      { q: 'How much pea gravel per square foot?', a: 'At 2 inches deep: 1 cubic yard covers 162 sq ft. At 3 inches: covers 108 sq ft. At 6 inches (playground minimum): covers 54 sq ft. Multiply your square footage by your depth in inches, divide by 324 for cubic yards.' },
      { q: 'How much does a 50-lb bag of pea gravel cover?', a: 'A 50-lb bag holds about 0.019 cubic yards. At 2 inches deep, one bag covers roughly 3 sq ft. At 6 inches deep, one bag covers about 1 sq ft. For any playground or area over 50 sq ft, bulk delivery by the ton is significantly cheaper.' },
      { q: 'Does pea gravel need to be compacted?', a: 'No - pea gravel cannot be effectively compacted because the smooth rounded edges prevent interlocking. This is a feature for playgrounds and drainage (loose stone absorbs impact and passes water), but it is why pea gravel is completely unsuitable for driveways and structural bases.' },
      { q: 'Can I use pea gravel for a driveway?', a: 'No. Pea gravel shifts continuously under vehicle tires because the rounded stones cannot interlock or lock together under compaction pressure. It creates a dangerous loose surface, ruts deeply, and migrates off the driveway edge. Use angular #57 crushed stone for driveways instead.' },
      { q: 'How much pea gravel for a fire pit area?', a: 'A 10×10 ft fire pit surround at 2 inches deep needs 0.62 cubic yards (about 0.8 tons). Pea gravel is a good fire pit surround material - it does not burn, does not shift significantly in that role, and looks clean. Keep a border edging in place to prevent migration.' },
      { q: 'What size is pea gravel?', a: 'Standard pea gravel ranges from 1/4" to 3/8" in diameter. The "pea" name refers to its smooth, rounded shape and approximate size relative to a green pea. Confirm the exact size range with your supplier if you need a specific diameter for drainage pipe bedding or playground safety documentation.' },
    ],
    materialInfo: 'Pea gravel is smooth, water-worn stone ranging from 1/4" to 3/8" in diameter. The rounded shape is what defines both its best and worst properties. Because the edges are smooth, individual stones roll freely against each other - they cannot interlock the way angular crushed stone does. No amount of compaction will stabilize pea gravel into a load-bearing surface. This is why it is excellent for playground safety (the loose surface absorbs impact energy), effective for drainage blankets (the void space passes water freely), and completely wrong for driveways and structural bases.\n\nFor playground safety, depth requirements under ASTM F1292 are not optional guidelines - they are safety minimums derived from testing at specific fall heights. A residential swing set 7 feet tall at its highest accessible point requires 12 inches of pea gravel in the fall zone, not 6 inches. The critical fall height is measured from the highest point a child can stand or sit, not the overall equipment height. Getting this wrong is a liability issue, not just an aesthetic one.\n\nPea gravel weighs 1.3 tons per cubic yard - slightly less than crushed stone (1.4 tons/yd³) because the void space between the rounded stones is larger than between angular stone. This difference matters when ordering by weight: a ton of pea gravel delivers slightly more volume than a ton of crushed stone.',
