    faqs: [
      { q: 'How much sand do I need?', a: 'Multiply length (ft) × width (ft) × depth (in), then divide by 324 for cubic yards. A 100 sq ft paver bed at 1 inch deep needs 0.31 cubic yards. A 6×6 ft sandbox at 6 inches deep needs 0.67 cubic yards. The calculator above handles this for any dimensions.' },
      { q: 'What type of sand do I need under pavers?', a: 'You need coarse concrete sand, also called manufactured sand or ASTM C33 sand. Its angular particles lock together under the weight of pavers and resist lateral migration. Play sand, mason sand, and limestone screenings are all too fine - they wash out or shift, causing pavers to sink and rock within one season.' },
      { q: 'How much sand do I need for a paver base?', a: 'A standard 1-inch bedding sand layer needs 0.31 cubic yards per 100 square feet (about 0.42 tons). A 10×12 ft patio needs 0.37 cubic yards. A 16×20 ft patio needs 0.99 cubic yards. Always screed to exactly 1 inch - more than 1.5 inches causes instability.' },
      { q: 'How much sand do I need in tons?', a: 'Sand weighs 1.35 tons per cubic yard when dry. Calculate your cubic yards (length × width × depth ÷ 324), then multiply by 1.35 for tons. Wet sand can weigh up to 1.5 tons per cubic yard - a difference worth knowing when comparing supplier quotes.' },
      { q: 'How many 50-lb bags of sand do I need?', a: 'One cubic yard of sand equals about 54 bags of 50-lb sand. A small 10×10 paver patio (at 1 inch depth) needs 0.31 cubic yards - about 17 bags. For any area over 100 square feet, bulk delivery is significantly cheaper than bags.' },
      { q: 'How much sand for a sandbox?', a: 'A 6×6 ft sandbox at 6 inches deep needs 0.67 cubic yards (about 0.9 tons or 36 bags of 50-lb play sand). A 4×6 ft sandbox at 6 inches needs 0.44 cubic yards. Use only washed play sand in sandboxes - not construction sand or fill sand, which may contain silica fines and debris.' },
      { q: 'How deep should sand be under pavers?', a: 'Exactly 1 inch of coarse concrete sand. This is an engineering requirement, not a guideline. Less than 1 inch provides inadequate leveling ability. More than 1.5 inches creates a soft, unstable bed that allows pavers to rock and sink under load. Screed to 1 inch using 1-inch diameter screed pipes as guides.' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between play sand and concrete sand?', a: 'Play sand has round, smooth particles - safe for children to handle, but structurally useless. Concrete sand has angular, sharp particles that lock together under compaction. Use play sand in sandboxes. Use concrete sand (ASTM C33) for all structural applications: paver beds, concrete mixes, mortar, and leveling courses.' },
    ],
    materialInfo: 'Sand particle shape is the most important variable in selecting the right type. Angular sand (concrete sand, manufactured sand) has fractured edges that lock together under compaction - it resists lateral movement and spreads load evenly. Round sand (play sand, beach sand) has smooth polished surfaces that allow particles to slide freely, making it structurally useless under any load.\n\nThe four sand types you will encounter at suppliers are: coarse concrete sand (ASTM C33 - angular, for paver beds and concrete); play sand (fine, round, washed - for sandboxes only); mason sand (fine, for mortar and stucco joints); and utility fill sand (variable quality, for backfill and drainage). These are not interchangeable. Using play sand under pavers is the single most common cause of paver settlement in residential installations.\n\nWet sand weighs about 10% more than dry sand. Most bulk suppliers weigh material at the quarry after it has been in outdoor storage, meaning it is almost always wet. If your calculator shows 1.35 tons and the supplier quotes a wet-weight price, the delivered volume will be slightly less than a dry-weight order of the same tonnage. For critical applications, order by the cubic yard rather than by weight.',
